A Christian is an individual who adheres to [Christianity](/Christianity), a [monotheistic](/Monotheism) [Abrahamic religion](/Abrahamic_religion) rooted in the life and teachings of [Jesus Christ](/Jesus_in_Christianity). Christians constitute the world's largest religious community, numbering approximately 2.3 billion adherents. The term "Christ" and consequently "Christian" originates from the [Koine Greek](/Koine_Greek) title *Christós* (Χριστός), which is a translation of the [Biblical Hebrew](/Biblical_Hebrew) term *mashiach* (מָשִׁיחַ), commonly rendered as "messiah" in English. While interpretations of Christianity vary considerably, sometimes leading to conflict [11] [12], adherents are united by the belief in the unique significance of Jesus [11]. The adjective "Christian" is used to describe anything associated with Christianity or [Christian churches](/Christian_churches), and in a broader, proverbial sense, it can signify anything "noble, and good, and Christ-like" [13].

According to a 2011 survey by the [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center), the global Christian population stood at 2.3 billion, a notable increase from approximately 600 million in 1910. As of that survey, roughly 37% of Christians resided in the [Americas](/Americas), 26% in [Europe](/Europe), 24% in [sub-Saharan Africa](/Sub-Saharan_Africa), 13% in [Asia](/Asia) and the [Pacific](/Pacific), and a mere 1% in the [Middle East](/Middle_East) and [North Africa](/North_Africa) [3]. Christians form the majority population in 158 countries and territories, while approximately 280 million live as a [minority](/Minority_group). The [Catholic Church](/Catholic) accounts for about half of all Christians worldwide, with [Protestants](/Protestant) making up over a third (37%). [Eastern Christians](/Eastern_Christians), encompassing the [Eastern Orthodox](/Eastern_Orthodox), [Oriental Orthodox](/Oriental_Orthodox), and [Church of the East](/Church_of_the_East), represent 12% of the global Christian population [3]. Projections by the [Pew Research Center](/Pew_Research_Center) suggest that the Christian population will surpass 3 billion by 2050, driven by fertility rates [3]. This research also indicated that, should current demographic trends persist, Christianity will maintain its status as the [world's largest religion](/Major_religious_groups) in 2050. In recent history, Christians have faced varying degrees of [persecution](/Persecution_of_Christians), particularly in regions like the [Middle-East](/Christianity_in_the_Middle_East), North Africa, [East Asia](/East_Asia), and [South Asia](/South_Asia) [14] [15] [16].

Etymology

The Greek term Χριστιανός (*Christianos*), meaning "follower of Christ," is derived from Χριστός (*Christos*), meaning "anointed one" [17]. This Greek term was adopted with an adjectival suffix from Latin, signifying adherence to, or even possession by, a person. In the [Greek](/Greek_language) [Septuagint](/Septuagint), *christos* served as the translation for the [Hebrew](/Hebrew_language) term *Mašíaḥ* (מָשִׁיחַ), meaning "[one who is] anointed" [19]. Similar to English, other European languages adopted equivalent terms for "Christian," such as *chrétien* in French and *cristiano* in Spanish, all tracing back to the original Greek.

The abbreviations "Xian" and "Xtian" (and their related forms) have been in use since at least the 17th century. The [Oxford English Dictionary](/Oxford_English_Dictionary) notes the use of "Xtianity" in 1634 and "Xian" in a diary from 1634–38 [20] [21]. The abbreviation "Xmas" for Christmas employs a similar contraction.

Early Usage

The [Church of Saint Peter](/Church_of_Saint_Peter) near [Antioch](/Antioch), the city where the [disciples](/Disciple_(Christianity)) were first called "Christians," as depicted in modern times.

The earliest recorded instance of the term "Christian" or its [cognates](/Cognate) in other languages appears in the [New Testament](/New_Testament). In [Acts 11](/Acts_11), following Barnabas's recruitment of Saul (later Paul) in [Antioch](/Early_centers_of_Christianity), where they spent a year teaching the [disciples](/Disciple_(Christianity)), the text states that "the disciples were first called Christians in Antioch" ([Acts 11:26](/Acts_11:26)). A subsequent mention occurs in [Acts 26](/Acts_26), where [Herod Agrippa II](/Herod_Agrippa_II), in response to [Paul the Apostle](/Paul_the_Apostle), remarks, "Then Agrippa said unto Paul, Almost thou persuadest me to be a Christian" ([Acts 26:28](/Acts_26:28)). The final New Testament reference to the term is found in [1 Peter 4](/1_Peter_4): "Yet if [any man suffer] as a Christian, let him not be ashamed; but let him glorify God on this behalf" ([1 Peter 4:16](/1_Peter_4:16)) [23].

According to Kenneth Samuel Wuest, all three New Testament instances of the term carry a derogatory connotation, implying it was used to refer to followers of Christ who did not acknowledge the Roman emperor [24]. Antioch, the city where the name originated, was known for its propensity for coining such nicknames [25]. However, Peter's apparent acceptance of the term led to its adoption by the early believers, supplanting terms like "Nazarenes." The term *christianoi* became the standard designation in the writings of the [Early Church Fathers](/Early_Church_Fathers), beginning with figures like [Ignatius of Antioch](/Ignatius_of_Antioch) and [Polycarp](/Polycarp).

The earliest appearances of the term in non-Christian literature include the writings of [Josephus](/Josephus_on_Jesus), who referred to "the tribe of Christians, so named from him;" [27] as well as [Pliny the Younger](/Pliny_the_Younger) in his [correspondence with Trajan](/Epistulae_(Pliny)). [Tacitus](/Tacitus_on_Christ), writing in the early 2nd century, noted in his [Annals](/Annals_(Tacitus)) that "by vulgar appellation [they were] commonly called Christians" [28] and identified Christians as [Nero](/Nero)'s scapegoats for the [Great Fire of Rome](/Great_Fire_of_Rome) [29].

Nazarenes

The term "Nazarene" is another designation for Christians found in the New Testament. [Jesus](/Jesus) is referred to as a Nazarene in [Matthew 2:23](/Matthew_2:23), and Paul is described as such in [Acts 24:5](/Acts_24:5). The latter verse clarifies that "Nazarene" could refer to both a follower of Christ and the town of [Nazareth](/Nazareth) itself [original research? / citation needed].

The Jewish lawyer [Tertullus](/Tertullus), in his work *Against Marcion* (4:8), also used the term "Nazarene," recording the phrase "the Jews call us Nazarenes." Furthermore, around 331 AD, [Eusebius](/Eusebius) noted that Christ was called a Nazoraean from the name [Nazareth](/Nazareth), and that in earlier centuries, "Christians" were once known as "Nazarenes" [30]. The Hebrew equivalent, *Notzrim*, appears in the [Babylonian Talmud](/Babylonian_Talmud) and remains the modern Israeli Hebrew term for a Christian.

Modern Usage

The inscription *chrestianos*, the first known mention of Christians in [Tacitus' Annals](/Annals_(Tacitus)), found on an 11th-century copy. The [Latin cross](/Christian_cross) and [Ichthys](/Ichthys) are symbols frequently used by Christians to represent [their religion](/Christianity).

Definition

A wide spectrum of beliefs and practices exists among individuals who identify as Christian worldwide. The term "Christianity" itself is subject to diverse interpretations among different [denominations](/Christian_denomination) and sects. [Timothy Beal](/Timothy_Beal) highlights the variations in belief within the United States:

"Although all of them have their historical roots in Christian theology and tradition, and although most would identify themselves as Christian, many would not identify others within the larger category as Christian. Most Baptists and fundamentalists ([Christian Fundamentalism](/Christian_Fundamentalism)), for example, would not acknowledge Mormonism or Christian Science as Christian. In fact, the nearly 77 percent of Americans who self-identify as Christian are a diverse pluribus of Christianities that are far from any collective unity." [31]

[Linda Woodhead](/Linda_Woodhead) proposes a unifying element for Christians, stating, "Whatever else they might disagree about, Christians are at least united in believing that Jesus has a unique significance" [11]. [Michael Martin](/Michael_Martin_(philosopher)), in his analysis of three historical Christian creeds (the [Apostles' Creed](/Apostles%27_Creed), the [Nicene Creed](/Nicene_Creed), and the [Athanasian Creed](/Athanasian_Creed)), identified a set of core Christian tenets. These include belief in [theism](/Theism), the [historicity of Jesus](/Historicity_of_Jesus), the [Incarnation](/Incarnation_(Christianity)), [salvation](/Christian_soteriology) through faith in Jesus, and Jesus as an ethical role model [32].

Hebrew Terms

[Nazareth](/Nazareth), identified as the childhood home of [Jesus](/Jesus), lends its name to a term used in many languages as a general designation for those of the Christian faith [33].

Judaism does not accept the identification of Jesus as the Messiah. The Hebrew term for a Christian is נוֹצְרִי (*Notzri*, meaning "Nazarene"), a [Talmudic](/Talmud) term derived from Jesus's origin in the town of [Nazareth](/Nazareth) in Galilee. Adherents of [Messianic Judaism](/Messianic_Judaism) are referred to in modern Hebrew as יְהוּדִים מְשִׁיחִיִּים (*Yehudim Meshihi'im*, meaning "Messianic Jews").

Arabic Terms

In [Arabic-speaking cultures](/Arab_world), two primary terms are used for Christians: *Naṣrānī* (نصراني), plural *Naṣārā* (نصارى), which is generally understood to derive from "Nazarenes," followers of Jesus of Nazareth, via [Syriac](/Syriac_language) (Aramaic); and *Masīḥī* (مسيحي), meaning "follower of the Messiah" [35]. When a distinction is made, *Naṣrānī* often refers to individuals of Christian cultural background, while *Masīḥī* is used by Christians themselves to denote religious adherence to Jesus [36]. In certain countries, *Naṣrānī* can be used generically for non-Muslim Western foreigners [37].

Another Arabic word sometimes employed for Christians, particularly in a political context, is *Ṣalībī* (صليبي), meaning "Crusader," derived from *ṣalīb* (صليب, "cross"). This term can carry negative connotations [35] [38]. Historically, however, Muslim writers referred to European Christian Crusaders as *al-Faranj* or *Alfranj* (الفرنج), derived from the name of the [Franks](/Franks). This usage can be found in historical texts such as Ali ibn al-Athir's [Al-Kamil fi al-Tarikh](/Al-Kamil_fi_al-Tarikh) [40] [41].

In the [Maltese language](/Maltese_language), a Semitic language related to Arabic but written in the Latin alphabet, Christians are called *Nsara*, with the masculine singular being *Nisrani* [42]. The Romance-derived term *Kristjan* may also be encountered [43].

Asian Terms

