Socioeconomics

A 2016 study by the [Pew Center](/Pew_Center) on [religion and education](/Religiosity_and_education) globally found that Christians ranked as the second most educated religious group worldwide, after Jews, with an average of 9.3 years of schooling [73]. The highest average years of schooling among Christians were observed in [Germany](/Germany) (13.6), [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) (13.5), and [Estonia](/Estonia) (13.1) [73]. Christians also possessed the second-highest number of [graduate](/Academic_degree) and [post-graduate](/Post-graduate) degrees per capita, ranking first in absolute numbers (220 million) [73]. Among various [Christian communities](/World_Christianity), Singapore leads in the percentage of Christians holding university degrees (67%) [73], followed by [Christians in Israel](/Christianity_in_Israel) (63%), and [Christians in Georgia (country)](/Christianity_in_Georgia_(country)) (57%) [73].

The study indicates that Christians in [North America](/North_America), [Europe](/Europe), the [Middle East](/Middle_East), [North Africa](/North_Africa), and the [Asia Pacific](/Asia_Pacific) regions are highly educated. This is attributed, in part, to the historical establishment of numerous [universities](/Universities) by historic [Christian denominations](/Christian_denominations) [73]. The study also notes the historical role of "Christian monks [who] built libraries and, in the days before printing presses, preserved important earlier writings produced in Latin, Greek and Arabic" [73]. Furthermore, the study found significant [gender equality](/Gender_equality) in educational attainment among Christians. It suggests that one contributing factor was the encouragement of female education by the [Protestant Reformers](/Protestant_Reformers), which led to the eradication of illiteracy among women in Protestant communities [73].

Culture

Main article: [Christian culture](/Christian_culture)

"Christian identity" redirects here. For the white supremacist religion, see [Christian Identity](/Christian_Identity).

A collection of images showcasing [Christian culture](/Christian_culture) and notable Christian figures.

[Christian culture](/Christian_culture) encompasses the diverse cultural practices prevalent among Christian peoples. Variations in the application of Christian beliefs are evident across different cultures and traditions [75]. Christian culture has significantly influenced and assimilated elements from the [Greco-Roman](/Greco-Roman_world), [Byzantine](/Byzantine_Empire), [Western culture](/Western_culture) [76], [Middle Eastern](/Christianity_in_the_Middle_East) [77] [78], [Slavic](/List_of_Slavic_cultures) [79], [Caucasian](/Caucasus) [79], and [Indian cultures](/Culture_of_India).

Following Christianity's expansion from the [Levant](/Levant) into Europe, North Africa, and the [Horn of Africa](/Horn_of_Africa) during the early [Roman Empire](/Roman_Empire), Christendom became divided into the pre-existing [Greek East and Latin West](/Greek_East_and_Latin_West). This division resulted in the development of distinct Christian cultures, each with its own [rites](/Rite_(Christianity)) and practices. These cultures were often centered around major cities: Rome ([Western Christianity](/Western_Christianity)) and Carthage (forming what was known as Western or Latin [Christendom](/Christendom)) [80]; and Constantinople ([Eastern Christianity](/Eastern_Christianity)), Antioch ([Syriac Christianity](/Syriac_Christianity)), Kerala ([Indian Christianity](/Christianity_in_India)), and Alexandria, among others, which constituted Eastern or Oriental Christendom [81] [82] [83]. The [Byzantine Empire](/Byzantine_Empire) represents a significant epoch in [Christian history](/Christian_history) and the development of [Christian civilization](/Christian_civilization) [83]. From the 11th to the 13th centuries, [Latin Christendom](/Latin_Christendom) rose to prominence, playing a central role in shaping the [Western world](/Western_world) and [Western culture](/Western_culture) [84].

For much of its history, Western culture has been largely synonymous with Christian culture, and a substantial portion of the Western Hemisphere's population can be described as practicing or nominal Christians. The concepts of "Europe" and the "Western World" have been intrinsically linked with "Christianity and Christendom" [84]. Beyond the Western sphere, Christians have made impactful contributions to various cultures across Africa, the Near East, Middle East, East Asia, Southeast Asia, and the Indian subcontinent [85] [86].

Christians have made notable contributions across numerous fields, including philosophy [87] [88], [science and technology](/List_of_Christians_in_science_and_technology) [89] [90] [91] [92], [medicine](/Catholic_Church_and_health_care) [93] [94], [fine arts and architecture](/List_of_Catholic_Church_artists) [95] [96], [politics](/Christianity_and_politics), literature [97], [music](/Christian_Music) [98], and [business](/Business) [99] [100]. A review of Nobel Prizes awarded between 1901 and 2000 revealed that 65.4% of laureates identified Christianity in its various forms as their religious preference [101].

Persecution

Main article: [Persecution of Christians](/Persecution_of_Christians)

See also: [Anti-Christian sentiment](/Anti-Christian_sentiment)

In 2017, [Open Doors](/Open_Doors), a [human rights NGO](/List_of_Christian_human_rights_non-governmental_organisations), estimated that approximately 260 million Christians worldwide experience "high, very high, or extreme persecution" annually [102]. North Korea was identified as the most dangerous nation for Christians [103] [104].

A 2019 report [105] [106], commissioned by the United Kingdom's [Secretary of State](/Secretary_of_State_for_Foreign_and_Commonwealth_Affairs) for the [Foreign and Commonwealth Office](/Foreign_and_Commonwealth_Office), investigated the global persecution of Christians. It found that [religious persecution](/Religious_persecution) has escalated, with the highest levels observed in the Middle East, North Africa, India, China, North Korea, and Latin America, among other regions [15]. The report emphasized that this persecution is a global phenomenon, not confined to Islamic states [106]. The investigation concluded that approximately 80% of persecuted believers globally are Christians [16].

